WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.119
Bem-vindo de volta!

00:00:02.119 --> 00:00:04.729
Na última vez você viu os comandos

00:00:04.729 --> 00:00:05.475
de fork.

00:00:05.475 --> 00:00:08.085
Agora vamos ver o que eles significam

00:00:08.085 --> 00:00:08.831
na prática:

00:00:08.831 --> 00:00:11.441
um app de banco de dados ao

00:00:11.441 --> 00:00:11.814
vivo,

00:00:11.814 --> 00:00:12.933
copiado em segundos,

00:00:12.933 --> 00:00:13.679
editado livremente,

00:00:13.679 --> 00:00:15.916
enquanto o original nem percebe nada.

00:00:16.684 --> 00:00:18.444
Veja o cenário:

00:00:18.444 --> 00:00:21.378
um PostgreSQL de verdade com

00:00:21.378 --> 00:00:24.311
uma interface pgAdmin por cima,

00:00:24.311 --> 00:00:26.658
ao vivo no servidor.

00:00:26.658 --> 00:00:29.591
Um fork é uma cópia

00:00:29.591 --> 00:00:32.525
gêmea instantânea de tudo isso,

00:00:32.525 --> 00:00:33.698
com copy-on-write.

00:00:33.698 --> 00:00:36.045
Mesmos dados no início,

00:00:36.045 --> 00:00:38.392
vidas completamente separadas depois.

00:00:41.671 --> 00:00:43.377
Meet the app:

00:00:43.377 --> 00:00:43.946
demo-pgadmin,

00:00:43.946 --> 00:00:46.789
a PostgreSQL with a pgAdmin

00:00:46.789 --> 00:00:47.358
interface,

00:00:47.358 --> 00:00:49.064
mounted and running.

00:00:52.064 --> 00:00:53.772
Um repo ativo.

00:00:53.772 --> 00:00:54.911
Vamos cloná-lo.

00:00:55.404 --> 00:00:57.395
Aqui está o original,

00:00:57.395 --> 00:00:58.390
no navegador.

00:00:58.390 --> 00:01:00.380
O pgAdmin pede login,

00:01:00.380 --> 00:01:03.365
porque é a cópia de produção,

00:01:03.365 --> 00:01:05.853
e a produção fica protegida.

00:01:29.071 --> 00:01:29.842
Fork it.

00:01:29.842 --> 00:01:32.541
The copy-on-write clone takes seconds regardless of

00:01:32.541 --> 00:01:32.927
size;

00:01:32.927 --> 00:01:35.626
detach returns as soon as the containers

00:01:35.626 --> 00:01:36.011
start,

00:01:36.011 --> 00:01:38.710
while health checks continue in the background.

00:01:39.439 --> 00:01:40.951
Fork feito e iniciando.

00:01:40.951 --> 00:01:42.841
Os dados não foram copiados,

00:01:42.841 --> 00:01:43.597
foram compartilhados,

00:01:43.597 --> 00:01:45.865
até que um lado os altere.

00:01:49.138 --> 00:01:52.137
E aqui está o pgAdmin

00:01:52.137 --> 00:01:53.337
do fork.

00:01:53.337 --> 00:01:55.737
Sem login desta vez:

00:01:55.737 --> 00:01:58.136
forks são sandboxes descartáveis,

00:01:58.136 --> 00:02:01.136
então o bloqueio sai do

00:02:01.136 --> 00:02:01.736
caminho.

00:02:01.736 --> 00:02:02.936
Mesmas tabelas,

00:02:02.936 --> 00:02:04.136
mesmas linhas,

00:02:04.136 --> 00:02:06.535
mas um universo próprio.

00:02:42.038 --> 00:02:43.356
Two repositories now:

00:02:43.356 --> 00:02:45.553
the original and the experiment,

00:02:45.553 --> 00:02:47.751
each with its own containers,

00:02:47.751 --> 00:02:48.190
network,

00:02:48.190 --> 00:02:49.509
and disk view.

00:02:52.509 --> 00:02:53.585
Mesma máquina,

00:02:53.585 --> 00:02:55.199
dois mundos isolados.

00:02:58.508 --> 00:02:59.396
Done experimenting?

00:02:59.396 --> 00:03:00.728
Delete the fork.

00:03:00.728 --> 00:03:02.060
Seconds to create,

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:04.725
seconds to throw away — the

00:03:04.725 --> 00:03:06.945
original never knew it existed.

00:03:09.945 --> 00:03:10.491
Removido.

00:03:10.491 --> 00:03:13.217
O original continuou servindo o

00:03:13.217 --> 00:03:14.308
tempo todo.

00:03:15.106 --> 00:03:17.221
Então faça fork à vontade,

00:03:17.221 --> 00:03:19.335
a produção não corre risco.

00:03:19.335 --> 00:03:20.181
A seguir,

00:03:20.181 --> 00:03:21.450
falamos sobre secrets,

00:03:21.450 --> 00:03:23.988
a única coisa que seus forks

00:03:23.988 --> 00:03:25.257
deliberadamente não herdam.

00:03:25.257 --> 00:03:26.103
Até lá!
